{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|ほたる}}
{{swp|lang=ja|ホタル}}
From {{inh|ja|ojp|-}}. Appears in the ''{{w|Man'yōshú}}'', compiled some time after 759 CE.<ref name="MYS">{{RQ:Manyoshu|13|3344}}, text [http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man13Yo.html#3344 here]</ref>  Ultimate derivation {{unk|ja|nocap=1|sort=ほたる}}.
* The initial ''ho'' element is almost certainly the ancient form of {{m|ja|火|tr=hi||fire}}, which appears as ''ho'' in compounds such as {{m|ja|炎|tr=honō||flame|pos=originally from ''ho no ho''}} or {{m|ja|火屋|tr=hoya||lamp chimney}}.
* Various theories exist regarding the ''taru'' portion. This may be from classical verb {{m|ja|垂る|tr=taru||to hang down, to droop|pos=in reference to a firefly's posterior; modern form {{m|ja|垂れる|tr=tareru}}}}, or a vowel shift from verb {{m|ja|照る|tr=teru||to shine}}.

